\begin_layout Enumerate
The polynomial, sine, cosine, and exponential functions on the real line
 are all 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{\infty}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f'(x)=\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{3}x^{-2/3} & \mbox{for }x\neq0\\
\mbox{undefined} & \mbox{for }x=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 on the open subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x\in\mathbb{R}\mid x\neq0\}\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{x}f(t)dt=\int_{0}^{x}t^{1/3}dt=\frac{3}{4}x^{4/3}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula $g'(x)=f(x)=x^{1/3}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{1}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{2}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 In the same way one can construct a function that is 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{k+1}$
\end_inset

 at a given point.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 be given by 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

