\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consider the norm function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, given by sending 
\begin_inset Formula $x=(x_{1},\dots,x_{n})\in\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=\sqrt{x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We will do this in detail.
 First we claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial and 
\begin_inset Formula $k\geq1$
\end_inset

.
 We prove this by induction on 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case is trivial: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)=\frac{x_{n}}{\|x\|}
\]

\end_inset

Now suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\partial_{x_{n}}^{k+1}\left(\|x\|\right) & =\partial_{x_{n}}\left(\frac{f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}\right)\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{n}}f)(x)}{\|x\|^{2k-1}}+\frac{(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2k+1}}\\
 & =\frac{(\partial_{x_{1}}f)(x)\left(x_{1}^{2}+\cdots+x_{n}^{2}\right)+(1-2n)x_{n}f(x)}{\|x\|^{2n+1}}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This establishes our claim.
 Now given that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{n}}^{k}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)/\|x\|^{2k-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial, it is clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{x_{1}}^{k_{1}}\cdots\partial_{x_{n}}^{k_{n}}\left(\|x\|\right)$
\end_inset

 has the form 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)/\|x\|^{2(k_{1}+\cdots+k_{n})-1}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial (just use the same induction proof).
 Now since 
\begin_inset Formula $\|x\|=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, we see that the norm function is smooth in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}\backslash\{\mathbf{0}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

